\section*{Solution}

The gain in kinetic energy is equal to the loss of potential energy:

\begin{equation}
    \frac{1}{2}mv^2 = mg(h - 2R)
\end{equation}

Solving for \(v^2\), we have:

\begin{equation}
    v^2 = 2g(h - 2R) \tag{1}
\end{equation}

The force exerted on the track at the top is given by:

\begin{equation}
    F = \frac{mv^2}{R} - mg \tag{2}
\end{equation}

According to the problem, the force \(F\) is equal to the gravitational force:

\begin{equation}
    F = mg \tag{3}
\end{equation}

Therefore, equating (2) and (3), we get:

\begin{equation}
    \frac{mv^2}{R} - mg = mg
\end{equation}

Simplifying, we find:

\begin{equation}
    v^2 = 2gR \tag{4}
\end{equation}

Using equation (4) in equation (1), we find:

\begin{equation}
    2g(h - 2R) = 2gR
\end{equation}

Solving for \(h\), we obtain:

\begin{equation}
    h = 3R
\end{equation}

